questions.question:
Identify and correct three fundamental compile-time errors in the following snippet:

class Dog {
    std::string name;
    void speak() {
        std::cout << name << " says woof!";
    }
}

int main() {
    Dog myDog;
    myDog.name = "Rex";
    myDog.speak();
}

questions.answer:
Fixes:
1. Missing semicolon at the end of class declaration line 7 ('};').
2. 'name' and 'speak' default to 'private' access since they are inside a 'class' without explicit public flags. They must be grouped under a 'public:' specifier to be accessed in 'main'.

Corrected Code:
class Dog {
public:
    std::string name;
    void speak() {
        std::cout << name << " says woof!\n";
    }
};

questions.question:
A junior engineer wrote this code expecting it to update and print coordinates, but it fails compilation. Debug the code and explain why it failed:

class Point {
private:
    int x = 0;
    int y = 0;
public:
    void setX(int x) const {
        x = x;
    }
    void print() const {
        std::cout << "(" << x << ", " << y << ")\n";
    }
};

questions.answer:
Errors and Fixes:
1. 'setX' is declared as a 'const' member function. A const member function guarantees it will not alter class member states. Mutating 'x' inside it triggers a compilation error.
2. The expression 'x = x;' inside 'setX' is assigning the local parameter 'x' to itself due to parameter shadowing. It fails to touch the actual class member variable. This must be resolved by using 'this->x = x;' after removing the const qualifier.

Corrected Code:
void setX(int x) {
    this->x = x;
}

class SecureWallet {
private:
    double balance = 0.0;
public:
    bool deposit(double amount) {
        if (amount <= 0.0) return false;
        balance += amount;
        return true;
    }
    bool withdraw(double amount) {
        if (amount <= 0.0 || (balance - amount < 0.0)) return false;
        balance -= amount;
        return true;
    }
    [[nodiscard]] double getBalance() const {
        return balance;
    }
};

class UniqueSystemHandle {
private:
    int handleId = 0;
public:
    void setHandle(int id) { this->handleId = id; }
    [[nodiscard]] int getHandle() const { return handleId; }

    bool copyFrom(const UniqueSystemHandle& other) {
        // Compare pointer address of 'this' to the address of 'other'
        if (this == &other) {
            return false; // Prevent redundant self-assignment
        }
        this->handleId = other.handleId;
        return true;
    }
};

